<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="46" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,319,517,542]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body subcylindrical, almost parallel-sided; pronotum with antescutellar fovea, anterior and posterior angles rounded; prosternum broad, rounded at the base; carinal stria “U”-shaped; sutural region of elytra concave; protibiae with 
<number box="[392,406,589,613]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
or 
<number box="[452,466,589,613]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="6.0">6</number>
teeth; first abdominal sternum with large punctuation on the posterior region, first abdominal sternum stria present anteriorly and laterally; propygidium and pygidium with deep punctuation; pygidium with a transverse elevation medially.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="46" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,371,697,722]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Redescription.</emphasis>
Length (pronotum + elytra): 
<quantity box="[712,867,697,721]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.045" metricValueMax="7.49" metricValueMin="6.6" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="7.045" valueMax="7.49" valueMin="6.6">6.6–7.49 mm</quantity>
; width: 
<quantity box="[962,1102,697,721]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.35" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" unit="mm" value="3.35" valueMax="4.5" valueMin="2.2">2.2–4.5 mm</quantity>
. Body subcylindrical, almost parallel sided; dark; shining (
<figureCitation box="[478,546,733,757]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[186,1411,205,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[170,1430,195,1933]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal and ventral habitus photographs of type material and type labels. A-B. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885; C-D. Ebonius lineiger (Marseul, 1870); E-F. Ebonius aequatorius Lewis, 1910." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[530,546,733,757]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Head with irregular, strong and dense punctuation; frontal disc with a deep impression in the middle; occipital, supraorbital and frontal striae well marked; frontoclypeal suture present laterally (
<figureCitation box="[1062,1129,805,829]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,897,920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,375,872]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,375,872]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885 photographs A. Frontal view; B. Pygidium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201735/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1114,1129,805,829]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Labrum subrectangular. The left mandible with a long tooth on the internal margin. Antennae with scape slender at the base; last antennomeres from funicle with lateral setae; antennal club with well-marked sutures and the last segment with an apical depression.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Pronotum subquadrangular, 
<number box="[512,547,949,973]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="1.4">1.4</number>
times as wide as long, with slightly raised sides; punctuation dense and regular; anterior margin with a complete marginal stria (
<figureCitation box="[686,754,985,1009]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,897,920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,375,872]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,375,872]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885 photographs A. Frontal view; B. Pygidium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201735/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[739,754,985,1009]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A); lateral stria complete, and laterally confluent with pronotal margin; posterior region with rounded edges and an antescutellar fovea (
<figureCitation box="[1008,1074,1021,1045]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[186,1411,205,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[170,1430,195,1933]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal and ventral habitus photographs of type material and type labels. A-B. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885; C-D. Ebonius lineiger (Marseul, 1870); E-F. Ebonius aequatorius Lewis, 1910." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1061,1074,1021,1045]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E). Prosternum with large punctuation, an orifice on each side of the anterior margin and near the procoxal cavities; prosternal keel large and flat; “U”-shaped carinal stria; posterior margin of prosternum rounded; prosternal lobe rounded in the middle of the anterior margin and marginal stria complete (
<figureCitation box="[658,724,1129,1153]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[186,1411,205,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[170,1430,195,1933]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal and ventral habitus photographs of type material and type labels. A-B. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885; C-D. Ebonius lineiger (Marseul, 1870); E-F. Ebonius aequatorius Lewis, 1910." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[710,724,1129,1153]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B, D, F).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Elytra with well-marked striae, external subhumeral stria long; sutural region concave and sutural stria long (
<figureCitation box="[159,225,1201,1225]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[186,1411,205,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[170,1430,195,1933]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal and ventral habitus photographs of type material and type labels. A-B. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885; C-D. Ebonius lineiger (Marseul, 1870); E-F. Ebonius aequatorius Lewis, 1910." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,225,1201,1225]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
A, C, E). Mesosternum widely emarginated anteriorly; mesosternal marginal stria complete (
<figureCitation box="[1270,1336,1201,1225]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[186,1411,205,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[170,1430,195,1933]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal and ventral habitus photographs of type material and type labels. A-B. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885; C-D. Ebonius lineiger (Marseul, 1870); E-F. Ebonius aequatorius Lewis, 1910." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1322,1336,1201,1225]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B, D, F). Metasternum finely punctuated on the disc, with lateral metasternal stria complete and ending close to the metasternal-mesepimeral suture.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Anterior femur with strong and dense punctuation; anterior tibia with 
<number box="[977,991,1309,1333]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
or 
<number box="[1027,1041,1309,1333]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="6.0">6</number>
teeth on the external margin; tarsal cavity straight. Meso and metatibiae with the apical tooth widened and adorned with four short spines, metatibiae with 
<number box="[208,249,1381,1405]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
teeth on the external margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
First abdominal sternum with large punctuation on the lateral region and posterior margin, with a stria present along anterior and lateral margins (
<figureCitation box="[556,625,1453,1477]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1948,1971]" captionTargetBox="[186,1411,205,1931]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[170,1430,195,1933]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Dorsal and ventral habitus photographs of type material and type labels. A-B. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885; C-D. Ebonius lineiger (Marseul, 1870); E-F. Ebonius aequatorius Lewis, 1910." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201736/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[611,625,1453,1477]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="3.0">3</number>
</figureCitation>
B, D, F). Propygidium and pygidium with irregular and deep punctuations, the latter with the anterior margin straight and a transverse elevation medially (
<figureCitation box="[1104,1172,1489,1513]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,897,920]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,375,872]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1436,375,872]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885 photographs A. Frontal view; B. Pygidium." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201735/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1156,1172,1489,1513]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Female genitalia as observed in the type-species: coxites at least twice as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[1203,1272,1525,1549]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,939,962]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,211,905]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[188,1399,193,918]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, female genitalia. A. Coxites, ventral view, scale 1 mm.; B. Detail of stylus, scale 0.5 mm.; C. Bursa copulatrix, vagina, spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.5 mm.; D. Detail from spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201737/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1257,1272,1525,1549]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A), and with a subapical lateral projection next the cavity for insertion of stylus (
<figureCitation box="[884,951,1561,1585]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,939,962]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,211,905]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[188,1399,193,918]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, female genitalia. A. Coxites, ventral view, scale 1 mm.; B. Detail of stylus, scale 0.5 mm.; C. Bursa copulatrix, vagina, spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.5 mm.; D. Detail from spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201737/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[936,951,1561,1585]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
A, B). Duct of spermatheca inserted on apical region of bursa copulatrix (
<figureCitation box="[506,575,1597,1621]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,939,962]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,211,905]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[188,1399,193,918]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, female genitalia. A. Coxites, ventral view, scale 1 mm.; B. Detail of stylus, scale 0.5 mm.; C. Bursa copulatrix, vagina, spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.5 mm.; D. Detail from spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201737/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[560,575,1597,1621]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D). Spermatheca elongated with constraining rings (
<figureCitation box="[1205,1276,1597,1621]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,939,962]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,211,905]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[188,1399,193,918]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, female genitalia. A. Coxites, ventral view, scale 1 mm.; B. Detail of stylus, scale 0.5 mm.; C. Bursa copulatrix, vagina, spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.5 mm.; D. Detail from spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201737/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1260,1276,1597,1621]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
D). Accessory spermatic gland elongated and bigger than spermatheca (
<figureCitation box="[788,855,1633,1657]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="6.[151,250,939,962]" captionTargetBox="[188,1395,211,905]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[188,1399,193,918]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 4. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, female genitalia. A. Coxites, ventral view, scale 1 mm.; B. Detail of stylus, scale 0.5 mm.; C. Bursa copulatrix, vagina, spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.5 mm.; D. Detail from spermatheca and accessory spermatic gland, scale: 0.25 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201737/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[840,855,1633,1657]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
C, D).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Male genitalia as observed in the 
<typeStatus box="[577,625,1670,1694]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">type</typeStatus>
species: eighth tergite 
<number box="[885,920,1669,1693]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="1.3">1.3</number>
times as long as wide, basal margin emarginated and feebly emarginated apically, without apical stria (
<figureCitation box="[833,904,1705,1729]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[264,1324,219,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[240,1334,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, male genitalia. A. Eighth ventrite, dorsal view; B. Eighth tergite, dorsal view; C. Ninth ventrite, dorsal view; D. Ninth and tenth tergites, dorsal view; E. Edeagus, lateral view; F. Detail from parameres of the aedagus, ventral view. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201738/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[889,904,1705,1729]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
B); eighth ventrite composed of two sclerites, transversely cut and not pilose apically (
<figureCitation box="[601,668,1741,1765]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[264,1324,219,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[240,1334,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, male genitalia. A. Eighth ventrite, dorsal view; B. Eighth tergite, dorsal view; C. Ninth ventrite, dorsal view; D. Ninth and tenth tergites, dorsal view; E. Edeagus, lateral view; F. Detail from parameres of the aedagus, ventral view. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201738/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[654,668,1741,1765]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
A); ninth tergite elongated and pointed apically (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1278,1741,1765]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[264,1324,219,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[240,1334,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, male genitalia. A. Eighth ventrite, dorsal view; B. Eighth tergite, dorsal view; C. Ninth ventrite, dorsal view; D. Ninth and tenth tergites, dorsal view; E. Edeagus, lateral view; F. Detail from parameres of the aedagus, ventral view. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201738/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1264,1278,1741,1765]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D); ninth ventrite not &quot;Y&quot;-shaped, sclerotized and bilobed apically (
<figureCitation box="[762,829,1777,1801]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[264,1324,219,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[240,1334,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, male genitalia. A. Eighth ventrite, dorsal view; B. Eighth tergite, dorsal view; C. Ninth ventrite, dorsal view; D. Ninth and tenth tergites, dorsal view; E. Edeagus, lateral view; F. Detail from parameres of the aedagus, ventral view. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201738/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[815,829,1777,1801]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
C); tenth tergite bilobed apically, not setose (
<figureCitation box="[1333,1399,1777,1801]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[264,1324,219,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[240,1334,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, male genitalia. A. Eighth ventrite, dorsal view; B. Eighth tergite, dorsal view; C. Ninth ventrite, dorsal view; D. Ninth and tenth tergites, dorsal view; E. Edeagus, lateral view; F. Detail from parameres of the aedagus, ventral view. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201738/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1385,1399,1777,1801]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
D); aedeagus straight, feebly curved at the apex, 
<number box="[649,684,1813,1837]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="9.9">9.9</number>
times as long as wide at base of parameres, which are fused basally and dorsally separate on their apical fourth, becoming translucid and expanded (
<figureCitation box="[1050,1117,1849,1873]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[264,1324,219,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[240,1334,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, male genitalia. A. Eighth ventrite, dorsal view; B. Eighth tergite, dorsal view; C. Ninth ventrite, dorsal view; D. Ninth and tenth tergites, dorsal view; E. Edeagus, lateral view; F. Detail from parameres of the aedagus, ventral view. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201738/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[1103,1117,1849,1873]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
E, F); basal piece 
<number box="[1319,1368,1849,1873]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="0.36">0.36</number>
times as long as the parameres (
<figureCitation box="[440,506,1885,1909]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1560,1583]" captionTargetBox="[264,1324,219,1513]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[240,1334,193,1541]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Ebonius politus Lewis, 1885, male genitalia. A. Eighth ventrite, dorsal view; B. Eighth tergite, dorsal view; C. Ninth ventrite, dorsal view; D. Ninth and tenth tergites, dorsal view; E. Edeagus, lateral view; F. Detail from parameres of the aedagus, ventral view. Scale: 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/201738/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
Fig. 
<number box="[492,506,1885,1909]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" value="5.0">5</number>
</figureCitation>
E); gonopore of internal tube with its border finely serrated.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,480,2017]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1436,151,535]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="47" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,313,1922,1946]" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[321,413,1921,1945]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Ebonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[321,413,1921,1945]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Ebonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other Neotropical genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[883,1003,1921,1945]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Omalodini">Omalodini</taxonomicName>
in the following combination of characters: body cylindrical almost parallel-sided; antennae with subtriangular club (oval in 
<taxonomicName box="[1150,1290,1958,1981]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Scapomegas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1150,1290,1958,1981]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Scapomegas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Sphyracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Sphyracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); prosternum large, rounded at base (emarginated in 
<taxonomicName box="[785,925,1994,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Scapomegas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[785,925,1994,2017]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Scapomegas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and truncated in 
<taxonomicName box="[1121,1237,1993,2017]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Sphyracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1121,1237,1993,2017]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="46">Sphyracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and with carinal stria “U”-shaped (never “U”-shaped in other 
<taxonomicName box="[680,805,151,175]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Omalodini">Omalodini</taxonomicName>
); anterior margin of mesosternum widely emarginated (when compared to 
<taxonomicName box="[378,492,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Omalodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[378,492,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Omalodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); post-mesocoxal stria absent (present in 
<taxonomicName box="[966,1083,188,212]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Sphyracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[966,1083,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Sphyracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and in some species of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Scapomegas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Scapomegas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); sutural region of the elytra concave (flattened or weakly depressed in 
<taxonomicName box="[1026,1166,224,247]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Scapomegas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1166,224,247]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Scapomegas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1180,1294,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Omalodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1180,1294,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Omalodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Sphyracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Sphyracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); stria of the first abdominal sternum present anteriorly and laterally (absent on the anterior margin in other 
<taxonomicName box="[151,276,295,319]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Omalodini">Omalodini</taxonomicName>
); propygidium without tubercules (present in 
<taxonomicName box="[798,904,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Cornillus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[798,904,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Cornillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 
<taxonomicName box="[945,1059,296,320]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Omalodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[945,1059,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Omalodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and pygidium with a transverse elevation in the middle, both structures with large and deep punctuation (mostly with smaller and shallow punctuation in 
<taxonomicName box="[229,343,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Omalodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[229,343,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Omalodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[356,496,368,391]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Scapomegas" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[356,496,368,391]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Scapomegas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[550,667,368,392]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Sphyracus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[550,667,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Sphyracus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); male genitalia very similar to that illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Leivas" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" refString="Leivas, F. W. T. (2009) Estudo dos generos neotropicais de Omalodini Kryzhanovskij, 1972 (Coleoptera, Histeridae, Histerinae). Universidade Federal do Parana Press Curitiba, Parana, Brasil, 81 p." type="book" year="2009">
Leivas (
<number box="[1315,1376,367,391]" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" value="2009.0">2009</number>
: figs. 
<number box="[151,306,404,428]" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" value="69139.5" valueMax="138143.0" valueMin="136.0">136–138, 143</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for 
<taxonomicName box="[361,474,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Omalodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[361,474,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Omalodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[491,679,404,428]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Diplogrammicus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[491,679,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Diplogrammicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="47" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,151,535]" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,439,464]" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Distribution.</emphasis>
The species of 
<taxonomicName box="[540,632,440,464]" class="Insecta" family="Histeridae" genus="Ebonius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[540,632,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Ebonius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are limited to northern South 
<collectingCountry box="[989,1089,439,463]" name="United States of America" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">America</collectingCountry>
, being found in the following localities: 
<collectingCountry box="[267,433,476,500]" name="French Guiana" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">French Guiana</collectingCountry>
(Bélizon, Kourou, Montagne des Chevaux, Réserve des Nouragues, Itoupé – Mont tabulaire), 
<collectingCountry box="[224,292,511,535]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Brazil</collectingCountry>
(Pará and Amazonas) and 
<collectingCountry box="[594,687,511,535]" name="Ecuador" pageId="3" pageNumber="47">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(Canelos, Pastaza and Napo).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
